irector, and film producer. He is best known for directing the films ''[[101 Reykjav\u00edk]]'', ''[[The Sea (2002 film)|The Sea]]'', ''[[A Little Trip to Heaven]]'' (starring [[Julia Stiles]] and [[Forest Whitaker]]), a film based on the book [[Jar City]] by [[Arnaldur Indri\u00f0ason]], ''[[Contraband (2012 film)|Contraband]]'', ''[[2 Guns]]'' (starring [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Denzel Washington]]) and [[Everest (2015 film)|''Everest'']].\n\n==Life and career==\nKorm\u00e1kur was born in Reykjav\u00edk, Iceland. His father is the Catalan painter Baltasar Samper. His son is actor Baltasar Breki Samper.\n\nFor his film ''M\u00fdrin'', he won the [[Crystal Globe]] award at the [[Karlovy Vary International Film Festival]] in 2007. In December 2011, it was announced the production of a drama film ''Rocketman'' with Baltasar Korm\u00e1kur and [[Dagur K\u00e1ri]] was set to direct the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dagur Kari writing Icelandic film Rocket Man; Baltasar Kormakur to produce|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/production/dagur-kari-writing-icelandic-film-rocket-man-baltasar-kormakur-to-produce/5035735.article|accessdate=24 July 2013|newspaper=screendaily.com|date=15 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Contraband Director Baltasar Kormakur to Produce ROCKET MAN|url=http://www.filmofilia.com/contraband-director-baltasar-kormakur-to-produce-rocket-man-81079/|accessdate=24 July 2013|newspaper=filmofilia.com|date=15 December 2011}}</ref> His 2012 film ''[[The Deep (2012 film)|The Deep]]'' was selected as the Icelandic entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Oscar]] at the [[85th Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"Oscars\">{{cite news |url=http://svarthofdi.is/frett/djupid-framlag-islands-til-oskarsverdlaunanna | title= Dj\u00fapi\u00f0 framlag \u00cdslands til \u00d3skarsver\u00f0launanna |accessdate=25 September 2012 |date=25 September 2012 |work=svarthofdi.is}}</ref> making the January shortlist.<ref name=\"Oscar Shortlist\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2012/20121221.html |title=9 Foreign Language Films Vie For Oscar |accessdate=2012-12-21 |work=Oscars}}</ref> In January 2013, it was again announced that the film will be produced by Korm\u00e1kur with his partner Agnes Johansen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Baltasar Kormakur to produce Dagur Kari's Rocketman|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/production/baltasar-kormakur-to-produce-dagur-karis-rocketman/5050336.article|accessdate=24 July 2013|newspaper=screendaily.com|date=4 January 2013}}</ref> [[Denmark]]'s [[Nimbus Film]] will co-produce the film. The film's production started in February and will be filmed until the end of 2013, with an expected release in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oscar Hopeful Baltasar Kormakur to Produce Dagur Kari's 'Rocketman'|url=http://www.thewrap.com/movies/article/oscar-hopeful-baltasar-kormakur-produce-dagur-karis-rocketman-71426|accessdate=24 July 2013|newspaper=thewrap.com|date=4 January 2013}}</ref> In February 2015, it was announced that his next film would be the crime-thriller ''[[The Oath (2016 film)|The Oath]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=The Oath|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/indie/3331514/icelandic-director-dates-serial-killer-oath/|accessdate=24 July 2013|newspaper=thewrap.com|date=4 January 2013}}</ref> which is based on a script by actor \u00d3lafur Egilsson.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Oath|url=http://rvkstudios.is/production/film/#eidurinn|accessdate=24 July 2013|newspaper=RVK Studios|date=4 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009052358/http://rvkstudios.is/production/film/#eidurinn|archivedate=9 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!colspan=\"3\"|Credited as\n|-\n!width=65|Director\n!width=65|Producer\n!width=65|Writer\n|-\n|1996\n|''Go LazyTown''\n|{{Yes}}\n|{{No}}\n|{{Yes}}\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[101 Reykjav\u00edk]]''\n|{{Yes}}\n|{{Yes}}\